[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    11[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThis is the eighth recipe in Chapter 5 and the chapter's second Complex-tier recipe (four-star complexity). It introduces the recipe-specific concepts that distinguish it from the prior entity-resolution recipes (5.1 patient, 5.2 provider, 5.3 address, 5.4 eligibility, 5.5 cross-facility, 5.6 claims-clinical, 5.7 longitudinal-name-change): the matcher operates on cryptographically-transformed proxies of demographic features rather than on the features themselves; the privacy guarantee is a multi-organization contract enforced by cryptography rather than by BAA alone; the trust architecture (who is trusted to hold what) is a first-class architectural primitive that the protocol selection materializes; the salt is the cryptographic root-of-trust whose custody, rotation, and audit posture are load-bearing for the entire privacy claim; the accuracy ceiling is genuinely lower than direct matching and the institution has to choose use cases where the trade-off is acceptable; the operational rhythm includes salt rotation, parameterization upgrade, re-identification-risk review, and consent-withdrawal handling as recurring events rather than one-time concerns; and the regulatory context (post-Dobbs state-law overlays, 42 CFR Part 2, 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking, GDPR / PIPEDA / U.K. DPA cross-border applicability, the CMS Patient Access API ecosystem maturing into patient-mediated linkage) is more directly load-bearing than in any prior recipe in the chapter. The opening research-conference vignette earns its position: two people sitting at the same table for forty-five minutes about a GLP-1-and-MACE outcomes question with the clinical data at the academic medical center and the pharmacy fill data at the regional payer, neither party legally able to hand the other a flat file of demographics, both knowing the answer is in the intersection, sets up the cascade of operational vignettes (multi-site clinical trial pharmacy-fill verification, state cancer registry social-determinant-and-mortality-detail enrichment, ACO out-of-network ED visit attribution, precision-oncology research consortium across twenty academic medical centers and a sequencing vendor and tumor registries, post-state-law within-department immunization-registry-to-hospitalization-registry vaccine-effectiveness analysis, TEFCA QHIN-of-QHINs national-scale Medicare-Medicaid linkage, pharmaceutical-real-world-evidence platform with commercial tokenizer integration) at exactly the right level of "this is what privacy-preserving record linkage actually looks like in production" energy.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    12[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    13[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Technology section's "The Conventional Matcher Versus the Privacy-Preserving Matcher" subsection is the chapter's clearest articulation of what changes when the disclosure is constrained by cryptography rather than by a BAA. The "Three Families of PPRL Protocols" subsection (trusted-third-party tokenization model, Bloom-filter-based encoding model with CLK construction, secure-multi-party-computation and private-set-intersection model with garbled circuits, secret-sharing, oblivious transfer, homomorphic encryption, zero-knowledge proofs) is correct and at the right grain, with the operational-economics framing (most production deployments are tokenizer or Bloom-filter; SMPC is for special cases at small volumes) exactly right. The "What the Bloom Filter Encoding Actually Does" walk-through (bigram tokenization, k cryptographic hash functions parameterized by a shared salt, bit positions in a 1024-bit array, Sørensen-Dice coefficient on the encoded filters, the ~0.94 / ~0.85 / ~0.18 calibration examples for "John Smith" vs "Jon Smith" / "Jane Smith" / "Maria Garcia") is the recipe's strongest single passage of cryptographic pedagogy in the chapter. The "What the Matching Layer Has to Capture" eight-dimension enumeration (shared cryptographic salt and parameterization, protocol-specific trust architecture, linkage-result-disclosure policy, re-identification risk model, consent-and-purpose-of-use governance, linkage-performance-monitoring discipline, configuration-versioning and re-encoding lifecycle, cross-protocol bridge for hybrid deployments) is correct and recipe-specific. The "Why It Is Harder Than It Sounds" six-bullet enumeration (accuracy ceiling genuinely lower than direct matching, trust architecture non-trivial to negotiate, cryptographic-key management operationally heavier, protocol-execution coordination has its own failure modes, linkage results are themselves PHI in some scenarios, cohort-stratified accuracy disparities harder to detect and to fix) is correct and recipe-specific. The "Where the Field Has Moved" subsection (open-source toolkits maturing with [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140manonlink[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m / [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mclkhash[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m / [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mOpenMined PSI[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m / [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mMicrosoft SEAL[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m / [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mMP-SPDZ[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m, commercial tokenization consolidating with Datavant / HealthVerity / IQVIA, differential privacy as complementary primitive, TEE hardware enabling new patterns with Nitro Enclaves and SGX and SEV-SNP and Azure Confidential Computing, regulatory expectations tightening with Safe Harbor and Expert Determination and post-Dobbs and information-blocking, patient-mediated PPRL emerging through CMS Patient Access API) is correctly granular and forward-looking.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    14[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    15[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe six-stage architecture (prepare the demographic features for encoding, execute the agreed cryptographic encoding under the shared protocol parameterization, exchange the encoded data among participants under the trust architecture, run the matcher against the encoded data, persist the linkage results with disclosure-policy and audit metadata, react to events that supersede the linkage) is the right shape for the problem. The encoding-step elevation as the load-bearing addition versus recipe 5.5 ("a conventional cross-facility matcher operates on plaintext demographic features that flow through the HIE's matching layer. The PPRL matcher operates on cryptographically-encoded representations that are produced before any cross-organizational exchange") is the recipe's strongest single architectural primitive. Threshold calibration as protocol-specific (separate from recipe 5.5's plaintext thresholds; PPRL similarity scores are systematically lower for the same underlying record pair because of encoding noise) is correctly framed as discipline rather than convenience. Trust architecture as a first-class architectural concern ("the matcher's output is only as private as the protocol's trust assumption holds") is the right elevation. Disclosure-policy granularity (per-record-match-flags, intersection-count, k-anonymous-aggregate, differentially-private-aggregate, encrypted-match-indicator) as a multi-form mechanism the architecture supports simultaneously is recipe-specific and correctly architected. Cohort-stratified accuracy monitoring with privacy-preserving cohort-axis derivation (per-participant locally-computed cohort-axis hashes that the participants contribute in the encoding step; the matcher stratifies accuracy without learning the underlying axis values) is the recipe's strongest single operational primitive on the equity dimension. Salt rotation as the operational rhythm with dual-control approval and HSM custody is correctly elevated. Reversibility through re-encoding rather than retraction ("a linkage that was wrong cannot be retracted from a counterparty that has already consumed it; the only mitigation is to re-encode under a new parameterization, re-run the linkage, and disclose the corrected result") is the right framing. Consent withdrawal as forward-only with explicit patient-facing communication is the right discipline.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    16[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    17[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Honest Take is the recipe's most operationally pointed section, with twelve observations earning the recipe's voice: the technical-complexity-moderate-cryptographic-complexity-non-trivial-but-tractable-human-and-organizational-complexity-load-bearing framing (the recipe's strongest single observation about why PPRL is hard), the not-a-drop-in-replacement-for-direct-matching trap, the under-investing-in-trust-framework-negotiation trap (the recipe's strongest single trap on the human-and-organizational dimension), the under-investing-in-salt-management-ceremony trap, the trust-architecture-maintenance-as-operational-load observation, the commercial-tokenization-vendors-as-operationally-simpler-but-not-black-box observation, the academic-versus-operational-gap observation (the institution's privacy team must keep current with the literature), the cross-jurisdictional-overlays-as-recurring-regulatory-input observation, the consent-withdrawal-as-forward-looking-only observation with explicit patient-facing communication, the pilot-data-as-highest-value-and-highest-risk observation (separately governed substrate with its own contracts and infrastructure and lifecycle), the cross-recipe-coordination-with-subtle-ordering-effects observation, the would-do-differently-the-second-time observation on drafting the trust framework first, the regulatory-drift observation with the regulatory-monitoring function as the institutional response, and the closing PPRL-is-not-a-privacy-guarantee-it-is-a-privacy-preserving-exchange-mechanism observation that frames PPRL as one layer in a stack of privacy controls (k-anonymity, differential privacy, suppression of small cells, audit logging) rather than as the privacy guarantee itself. The Variations and Extensions section (trusted-third-party tokenization integration, TEE-based PPRL with Nitro Enclaves, patient-mediated PPRL through Patient Access API, differential-privacy-augmented disclosure, cross-cycle linkage composition with persistent encoded-record identifiers, federated SMPC across more than two parties, linkage-result-disclosure-policy templates per use case, cohort-stratified-accuracy monitoring with privacy-preserving cohort-axis derivation, active-learning-driven configuration tuning, re-identification-risk-aware adaptive parameterization, cross-jurisdictional overlay automation, audit-summary delivery to the patient) is well-scoped and frames each extension at the right grain.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    18[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    19[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThat said, two correctness-and-compliance gaps at HIGH severity need attention before publication, plus a recipe-specific set of MEDIUM and LOW items. (1) The architecture invokes a per-participant standardize-and-prepare Lambda, a per-participant bulk-encoding Glue job, a cross-account encoded-records exchange path with multiple transport types (tokenizer model, linkage-broker model, TEE-attested-endpoint model with Nitro Enclave attestation, SMPC protocol runner), a matcher Lambda or Nitro Enclave executor in the linkage-execution endpoint's account, a disclose-and-route Lambda, an invalidate-on-event Lambda consumed by salt-rotation events plus parameterization-upgrade events plus consent-withdrawal events plus identity-merge events from recipe 5.1 plus name-change events from recipe 5.7 plus re-identification-risk-model-update events, the cross-recipe EventBridge fan-out to consumers in 5.5 / 5.6 / 5.7 plus the analytic consumer plus per-participant operational systems, the salt-management ceremony with multi-party HSM custody and dual-control approval, and the patient-mediated PPRL trigger source from the Patient Access API; the identity-boundary checks on these paths are not specified at the architectural level. The recipe's own TODO at the IAM Permissions row names the chapter-wide pattern from 5.1 / 5.4 / 5.5 / 5.6 / 5.7 with explicit recipe-specific extensions (the salt-rotation ceremony's dual-control approval, the consent-withdrawal path's patient re-authentication, the cross-recipe EventBridge consumer-side validation with access-control-envelope-aware routing) but the architecture text does not actually specify the producer-signed envelope, the per-Lambda execution-role binding, the TEE attestation flow, or the cross-recipe event acceptance criteria. The consequence is uniquely sharp here because the salt is the cryptographic root-of-trust (a forged salt-rotation event with attacker-controlled [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mnew_salt_key_version[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m could invalidate the entire encoded-data corpus or, worse, surreptitiously substitute a salt the attacker knows; a forged consent-withdrawal-or-restoration event could remove patients from future linkages or surreptitiously add them; a forged parameterization-upgrade event could downgrade the defensive measures retroactively widening re-identification risk; a forged TEE attestation acceptance could route encoded data to a non-attested endpoint that the protocol's privacy claim does not cover; a forged invalidation event from a compromised cross-recipe source could mass-invalidate prior linkages forcing a re-encoding that exceeds the participants' coordination capacity). (2) The cohort-stratified accuracy monitoring is invoked with the privacy-preserving cohort-axis derivation correctly elevated as a recipe-specific architectural primitive ("the per-participant locally-computed cohort-axis hashes that the participants contribute in the encoding step; the matcher stratifies accuracy without learning the underlying axis values"), and the production-gaps section names the suggested values ("Cohort-stratified linkage-rate disparity > 0.05 = MEDIUM alarm; cohort-stratified false-acceptance-rate disparity > 0.01 = HIGH (because false acceptances under PPRL produce wrong-record disclosures that the consumer cannot retract)") with the recipe-specific addition of "the privacy team is an explicit reviewer for this recipe in addition to the standard analytics-governance committee, because cohort-stratified disparities in PPRL are also re-identification-risk indicators (cohorts with anomalously low linkage rates may be over-encoded with defensive noise; cohorts with anomalously high linkage rates may be under-encoded relative to the parameterization's defensive design)"; but the architecture pattern does not specify the cohort-axis enumeration, the disparity-calculation method, the per-metric emission cadence, or the remediation pathway. Same chapter pattern as 5.1 / 5.4 / 5.5 / 5.6 / 5.7 Finding A1; the cohort-distribution stakes are recipe-specific because cohort disparities are simultaneously fairness signals (some cohorts experience lower linkage rates and are under-represented in the analytic consumer's downstream output) and re-identification-risk signals (anomalous patterns suggest the parameterization's defensive design is mis-calibrated for those cohorts), and the cohort axes themselves are not directly observable on the encoded data which is structurally harder than in any prior recipe.[K
