[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    201[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;180;142;173m*[38;2;180;142;173m"Cohort-stratified accuracy monitoring uses the cohort-axis-hash labels contributed by each participant in the encoding step rather than the underlying axis values; the matcher and the metrics dashboard stratify by hash without learning the underlying axis values. Recipe-specific cohort axes (inherited from 5.7 plus PPRL-recipe-specific extensions): name-tradition cohort hash; transgender-or-gender-diverse cohort hash, populated only from patient-consented self-identification at each participant; age-decade cohort hash; name-change-frequency cohort hash; patient-consent-for-fairness-monitoring cohort hash (fairness-monitoring opt-in versus opt-out); cross-jurisdictional-overlay cohort hash (post-Dobbs reproductive-health-care state-law overlay applicable, 42 CFR Part 2 substance-use-treatment-record applicable, cross-border GDPR / PIPEDA / U.K. DPA applicable, none-applicable). Metrics: (a) per-cohort linkage rate (computed weekly); (b) per-cohort false-acceptance rate (sampled audit, computed weekly); (c) per-cohort review-queue aging (computed weekly); (d) per-cohort sampled error rate (computed monthly). Disparity calculation: absolute difference between the cohort with the highest rate and the cohort with the lowest rate, computed per-metric per-cycle. Alarm thresholds: linkage-rate disparity > 0.05 = MEDIUM; review-queue-aging disparity > 0.05 = MEDIUM; false-acceptance-rate disparity > 0.01 = HIGH (because false acceptances under PPRL produce wrong-record disclosures that the consumer cannot retract); any disparity > 2x the threshold = HIGH. Alarms route to the analytics governance committee, the equity-monitoring committee, the privacy team (which has explicit re-identification-risk-evaluation authority for this recipe), and (for cross-jurisdictional-overlay-affected cohorts) the institutional governance committee for cross-jurisdictional overlays, with a 5-business-day SLA for the first investigation report. The post-mortem and any remediation (per-cohort threshold tuning, per-cohort parameterization-tuning, per-tradition reference-data gap analysis, defensive-measures rebalancing) is documented in the cohort-disparity ledger and reviewed quarterly by the PPRL steering committee with privacy-team co-chair. The dual-interpretation translation is explicit: cohort-disparity metrics in this recipe are simultaneously fairness signals and re-identification-risk signals; cohorts with anomalously low linkage rates may be over-encoded with defensive noise (the parameterization is mis-calibrated); cohorts with anomalously high linkage rates may be under-encoded relative to the parameterization's defensive design (the parameterization may not be defending that cohort at the design's intended strength). The privacy team's re-identification-risk-evaluation is the authoritative determination on whether a cohort-disparity event requires defensive-measures-rebalancing in addition to threshold-tuning."[38;2;180;142;173m*[K
